{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519374"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:10:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:10:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12996"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12996"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.08,0.02,0.12,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5433"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46197"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5433"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12996"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31122"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"201"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2055"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9194"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9294"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44732"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46197"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents with a four month history of progressive shortness of breath and a persistent cough. He has worked as a plumber for over 30 years and believes he has been exposed to asbestos a number of times over his career. He is also a chronic smoker with 35 year smoking history with no history of alcohol intake or any substance abuse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 130/80 mmHg, pulse 78/min, temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 15/min with SpO2 95% on room air. On auscultation, crackles are heard at the base of the lungs at the end of the inspiration, with dual heart sounds. His nails have the following appearance (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray shows interstitial fibrosis and pleural thickening. Pulmonary function test shows mean DLCO measurement as 59.6% and FEV1/FVC ratio as 73.6%.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is he most likely at risk of developing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bronchogenic carcinoma","Hypercalcaemia","Tuberculosis","Caplan syndrome","Hypersensitivity pneumonitis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchogenic carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E- This patient\u0027s clinical picture is in keeping with asbestosis. The relevant risk factor is \u0026gt;20 years of asbestos exposure due to his occupation of plumbing. Other at-risk occupations include shipyard workers, miners, insulation installers, electricians, construction workers and navy personnel. Clinical features include progressive dyspnea, cough, chest pain and digital clubbing (as shown in the above image) which are typical for Interstitial lung disease (ILD). Asbestosis is a restrictive lung disease with decreased DLCO, FEV1 and FVC and increased FEV1/FVC ratio. The presence of a smoking history with asbestosis leads to a very high risk of carcinoma in such patients. The highest risk is of developing bronchogenic carcinoma that starts in the cells lining the bronchi and often presents as a cavitary lesion followed by risk of developing mesothelioma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypercalcaemia \u003C/strong\u003Edue to 1-alfa hydroxylase-mediated vitamin D activation in macrophages is seen in people with Sarcoidosis. These people also develop lung findings similar to asbestosis as sarcoidosis includes restrictive type interstitial lung disease presenting with chronic cough and progressive dyspnea. However, hypercalcemia is unrelated to asbestosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELatent tuberculosis \u003C/strong\u003Eoccurs in patients with silicosis. Clinical features are similar to asbestosis as silicosis is also a restrictive disease due to occupational exposure. But risk factors for the same include\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eexposure to silica dust, such as in miners, construction workers, and sandblasters. Chest X-ray shows egg-shell calcification of the hilar lymph nodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaplan syndrome \u003C/strong\u003Econsists of rheumatoid arthritis and pneumoconiosis with intrapulmonary nodules. It is associated with occupational lung diseases causing pneumoconiosis like asbestosis, silicosis, and anthracosis, and is not specific to asbestosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypersensitivity pneumonitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a lung disease caused by an allergic reaction to inhaled organic particles such as dust, mould, or animal dander. Clinical features include coughing, shortness of breath, and fever. Chest X-ray shows scattered micronodular interstitial opacities. It is not seen in patients who are exposed to asbestos.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Asbestosis is a restrictive lung disease caused by occupational exposure to asbestosis. It presents with progressive dyspnoea, basilar fine end-inspiratory crackles and digital clubbing. Presence of pleural plaques on chest imaging is the hallmark of asbestosis."],"references":["Musk AW, de Klerk N, Reid A, Hui J, Franklin P, Brims F. Asbestos-related diseases. Int J Tuberc Lung Dis. 2020 Jun 1;24(6):562-567. doi: 10.5588/ijtld.19.0645. PMID: 32553000.","Park EK, Yates DH, Wilson D. Lung Function Profiles among Individuals with Nonmalignant Asbestos-related Disorders. Saf Health Work. 2014 Dec;5(4):234-7. doi: 10.1016/j.shaw.2014.07.007. Epub 2014 Aug 7. PMID: 25516818; PMCID: PMC4266811."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31122"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12996"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20133"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20133"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7c7bafcc-6ceb-4c3d-ac51-81c1e421cad5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7c7bafcc-6ceb-4c3d-ac51-81c1e421cad5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":551}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31122"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-30T20:36:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-30T20:36:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5433"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46197"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type